# The Impact of Pollution on the East China Sea: A Comprehensive Analysis

The East China Sea (ECS), a marginal sea located between China, South Korea, Japan, and Taiwan, is a critical marine ecosystem that supports rich biodiversity and significant economic activities, including fisheries and shipping. However, rapid industrialization, urbanization, and agricultural expansion in the surrounding coastal regions of China have led to escalating pollution levels, severely impacting the ECS's ecological health. This report provides an in-depth, evidence-based analysis of how pollution affects the East China Sea, focusing on nutrient enrichment, eutrophication, harmful algal blooms (HABs), oxygen depletion, and broader ecological consequences.

---

## 1. Sources and Nature of Pollution in the East China Sea

Pollution in the ECS primarily originates from land-based sources, including industrial discharge, agricultural runoff, urban sewage, and atmospheric deposition. The Changjiang (Yangtze River) Basin, with a population exceeding 529 million by 2000, is a major contributor of nutrients and pollutants to the ECS ([Li & Daler, 2004](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0278434312001677)). The rapid increase in chemical fertilizer use since the 1960s has elevated nutrient concentrations in river waters, with dissolved inorganic nitrogen (DIN) and phosphate levels increasing by a factor of five by the late 1990s ([Wang, 2006](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0278434312001677)).

Additional pollution sources include:

- Untreated or partially treated sewage and industrial wastewater discharged into rivers and coastal waters.
- Atmospheric deposition of nitrogen and phosphorus compounds from agricultural and industrial emissions.
- Submarine groundwater discharge (SGD), which transports nutrients from terrestrial sources to coastal waters.
- Shipping accidents and marine spillage, contributing hydrocarbons and other pollutants ([Moxley, 2011](https://www.globalissues.org/news/2011/06/20/10157)).

---

## 2. Eutrophication and Nutrient Enrichment

### 2.1 Historical Trends

Eutrophication, the process of nutrient enrichment leading to excessive primary production, has been a pronounced issue in the ECS and adjacent China Seas over the past four decades. Studies indicate two distinct periods in the historical evolution of coastal eutrophication in China:

- **1980s to mid-2000s:** Rapid worsening of eutrophication, driven mainly by increased land-sourced nutrient inputs, particularly nitrogen and phosphorus from river discharge ([Wang et al., 2018](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0025326X1830691X)).
- **Last decade:** Implementation of control measures has curbed the worsening trend, though improvements remain modest due to ecosystem lag effects and accumulated nutrient loads ([Wang et al., 2018](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0025326X1830691X)).

### 2.2 Nutrient Composition and Stoichiometry

The nutrient composition in the ECS has shifted significantly, with increased nitrogen (N) and phosphorus (P) inputs altering the N:P ratio, which is critical for phytoplankton community structure and bloom dynamics ([Wang et al., 2021](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1568988321000883)).

| Nutrient Source       | Contribution to ECS Nutrient Load                      |
|----------------------|--------------------------------------------------------|
| River Input          | Major source, especially from Changjiang River          |
| Atmospheric Deposition| Significant input of nitrogen compounds                  |
| Submarine Groundwater Discharge (SGD) | Contributes nutrients, notably nitrogen and phosphorus |

---

## 3. Ecological Consequences of Pollution in the East China Sea

### 3.1 Harmful Algal Blooms (HABs)

The ECS has experienced a dramatic increase in the frequency, duration, and spatial extent of HABs, often referred to as "red tides" or "green tides," which are directly linked to nutrient enrichment. For example:

- The frequency of HABs increased from less than 10 events per year in the 1980s to 35–120 events per year since 2000 ([Wang et al., 2018a](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1568988321000883)).
- The total affected area has expanded to thousands or tens of thousands of square kilometers, with bloom durations extending from weeks to months ([Yu & Liu, 2016](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1568988321000883)).
- The largest algal bloom recorded in China occurred in the Yellow Sea in 2013, covering approximately 28,900 km², twice the size of the previous record in 2008 ([Mathiesen, 2013](https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/jul/04/china-algal-bloom-yellow-sea-green)).

HABs have detrimental effects on marine life, including fish kills, shellfish poisoning, and ecosystem disruptions, and pose threats to human health and local economies dependent on fisheries and tourism.

### 3.2 Oxygen Deficit and Hypoxia

Eutrophication-induced oxygen depletion is a critical environmental problem in the ECS:

- Oxygen deficits (hypoxia) have expanded in estuarine and coastal waters, particularly in the Changjiang Estuary and Pearl River Estuary ([Wang, 2009](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0025326X1830691X)).
- Hypoxia leads to the collapse of marine ecosystems and fishery resources, with increased abundance of hypoxia-tolerant species such as certain foraminifera ([Wei et al., 2011](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0025326X1830691X)).

### 3.3 Changes in Phytoplankton Community Structure

Nutrient enrichment and altered stoichiometry have shifted phytoplankton communities from diatom dominance toward increased dinoflagellate prevalence, which are often associated with HABs ([Zhou et al., 2019](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1568988321000883)). This shift affects food web dynamics and ecosystem functioning.

### 3.4 Broader Ecological Impacts

Other ecological consequences linked to pollution and eutrophication include:

- Increased jellyfish blooms, which can disrupt fisheries and marine ecosystems ([Sun, 2012](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0025326X1830691X)).
- Loss of submerged aquatic vegetation, changes in benthic communities, and epiphyte problems.
- Degradation of coral reefs and seaweed beds, with 86% of these habitats in Chinese coastal waters classified as below healthy standards ([Moxley, 2011](https://www.globalissues.org/news/2011/06/20/10157)).

